  "prompt": "What happens to a photon after it hits the retina of my eye?",
  "response": "When a photon enters the eye and hits the retina, it initiates a series of events that lead to visual perception. Here's a simplified overview of the process:\n\n1. **Absorption by Photoreceptors**: The retina contains photoreceptor cells called rods and cones. These cells contain light-sensitive molecules known as photopigments. When a photon hits one of these photopigments, it is absorbed, causing the photopigment to change its shape.\n\n2. **Phototransduction**: The change in shape of the photopigment molecules triggers a biochemical cascade inside the photoreceptor cell, known as phototransduction. This process results in the conversion of light into an electrical signal.\n\n3. **Signal Transmission**: The electrical signal is then passed on to the bipolar cells, and from there to the ganglion cells in the retina. The axons of the ganglion cells form the optic nerve.\n\n4. **Neural Pathway to the Brain**: The optic nerve carries the electrical signals from the retina to the brain, specifically to the visual cortex, which is located in the occipital lobe.\n\n5. **Perception and Interpretation**: Once the signals reach the brain, they are processed and interpreted to form the images you perceive.\n\nThroughout this process, the energy of the photon is effectively transformed into an electrochemical signal used by the nervous system, and the original photon does not continue to exist in its initial form.",
